O God! Thou art my God alone;  
Upon the wind, my longing flies.  
No other heart could be my own,  
No other voice could calm my cries.  

Through desert days and moonless years,  
Your shadow leads, Your silence speaks;  
A song of hope that dries my tears,  
A gentle hand for all who seek.  

What kings have built, the sands consume;  
What lovers swear, the years forget;  
But You remain, through light and gloom—  
My God, my soul’s eternal debt.

Light breaks where no sun shines;  
A shimmer at the edge of thought,  
Where grief has gathered, cold and fine,  
And every ordinary comfort’s naught.  

Still, through the cracks of loss and doubt,  
A phosphor glow begins to rise;  
Not from above, but deep within,  
A dawn unmeasured by the skies.  

Let every shadow have its hour;  
Let silence stretch across the years;  
Yet somewhere in the unmapped dark,  
A fragile brilliance appears.

Please spare me your secrets, let them wither in the dusk,
I am no vault for sorrow, no alchemist for husks.
Let your veils hang heavy, shimmering with doubt;
I choose the rhythm of sunlight, not the labyrinth without.

Let us trade in laughter, not in whispered dread;
Let the unsaid be petals scattered on the bed.
You keep your shadows—let me keep my day;
Please spare me your secrets, and let us drift away.
